India's New Hope
Cambridge, USA – India’s latest election may be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost ruled India since independence from Britain in 1947.
They might take heart from this decision.
The leader of the Congress Party and widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, Sonia Gandhi, has been effectively running the party since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh was merely a figurehead.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued a populist agenda, increased transfer payments, leading to India's annual growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi had promised rapid job and income growth across all of India during his campaign, as he did when he was Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state where economic activity expanded and attracted both domestic and foreign business investment.
A significant feature of the latest election was that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) achieved an absolute majority in the national parliament, which is arguably unprecedented in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will help Modi with his economic plans.
The new finance minister, Arun Jaitley, is politically experienced and served as a minister in the previous BJP government.
Jaitley is also known as a strategic thinker sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the governor of the Reserve Bank of India (central bank). Rajan is an outstanding economist who showed a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate during his tenure and attempted to reform some productivity constraints within India's financial sector.
Measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking steps to achieve faster long-term growth, you should look at progress in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of people can access the opportunities provided by these institutions because primary and secondary education in India is very backward.
Only 60% of Indian adults have basic literacy skills equivalent to primary school level.
Teachers themselves have inadequate educational qualifications and lack work motivation; many teachers do not even appear at their assigned schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport products nationwide and around the world.
The recent expansion of private air routes and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a role in this area.
Fiscal consolidation.
Massive budget deficits absorb national savings that should have been used to expand business investment. Budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxes.
Privatization.
The government-owned manufacturing and other industrial enterprises in India operate inefficiently and often result in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly contributes to accelerating economic growth.
Eliminate subsidies.
Power and energy subsidies lead to wasteful overconsumption and increased budget deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, cash transfers should be used instead. Currently, India's cash transfer system, which has introduced a remarkable new fingerprint-based cash transfer scheme, is quite efficient.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government buys, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is that large quantities of goods are stored in warehouses, while production incentives are misdirected.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and zoning.
Just by visiting Mumbai or other Indian metropolitan cities, you will see how zoning restrictions lead to inefficient land use in towns, hampering densification.
Inadequate clarity of property rights, particularly for agricultural land, has hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Relax foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot become controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex central and state sales tax regime distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a nationwide VAT and moving to a federal system has been ongoing for a long time, and should now enter the implementation phase.
Corruption.
Larger corruption cases at the higher levels have undermined economic confidence and also hindered official decision-making.
India is also grappling with petty corruption on a small scale, where bribery has become a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and limit petty corruption through new cash transfer payment systems.
Pulled by stronger growth and expectations of increased profits, India's stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party need to demonstrate to the world that they can fulfill their election promises.
